<ArticleLayout
  title="Cat Litter Trays in Australia: How to Choose Size and Style"
  seoTitle="Cat Litter Trays Australia: Size, Style and Setup"
  description="Plan tray number, location and cleaning access, then compare open, high-sided, low-entry and covered cat litter trays."
  category="Pets"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-20"
  faqs={faqs}
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/guides/pet-essentials-home-zones.webp"
  imageAlt="A dog resting in a practical pet zone with bedding, a lead, grooming supplies and clear household access"
>
  <p>
    A litter tray has to work for the cat before it works for the room. A hidden position may look
    tidier but fail if the route is noisy, blocked or difficult to reach. A compact tray may fit the
    laundry yet leave too little room for the cat to turn and dig.
  </p>
  <p>
    Plan the number and location first, then compare tray size, entry height, litter and cleaning
    access. The best setup is one the cat can use comfortably and the household can keep clean
    without constantly moving it.
  </p>
  <p>
    For the wider feeding, resting and cleaning plan, start with{" "}
    <a href="/guides/pet-essentials-for-australian-homes/">pet essentials for Australian homes</a>.
    This guide focuses on the tray decision and keeps the cat's access ahead of how discreet a
    product looks in the room.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose Quiet, Accessible Locations</h2>
  <p>
    Look for a position that offers some privacy without trapping the cat in a dead end. Avoid
    placing the tray beside food and water, in a route frequently blocked by a door, or next to a
    loud appliance that may start unexpectedly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check the route at different times of day. A laundry may be calm in the morning and crowded
    during washing. A bathroom door may be closed when guests visit. A balcony position may become
    inaccessible in bad weather or when the home is locked up.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan More Than One Tray Location</h2>
  <p>
    The <a href="https://kb.rspca.org.au/categories/companion-animals/cats/caring-for-my-cat/how-do-i-encourage-my-cat-to-use-a-litter-tray" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">RSPCA Knowledgebase litter tray guidance</a>{" "}
    recommends at least two trays for one cat and, for multiple cats, one tray per cat plus one.
    Those trays should be in physically separate locations so one access problem does not affect
    them all.
  </p>
  <p>
    Several trays lined up in one room do not provide the same choice as separate positions. In a
    multi-cat home, also consider whether one animal can watch or block the route used by another.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the Cat as Well as the Room</h2>
  <p>
    The RSPCA guidance suggests starting with a large open tray around one-and-a-half times the
    cat’s length. The cat needs room to enter, turn and dig without pressing against every side.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, compare:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>internal tray dimensions rather than the outer footprint alone</li>
    <li>entry height for kittens, older cats or cats with reduced mobility</li>
    <li>space to turn and position comfortably</li>
    <li>whether a cover reduces usable room or traps odour</li>
    <li>how easily the tray can be lifted, emptied and washed</li>
    <li>clearance around doors, cupboards and appliances</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Start Simply and Observe Preferences</h2>
  <p>
    Cats can have individual preferences for tray shape and litter. A large open tray with
    unscented litter is a practical starting point in the RSPCA advice, but the individual cat’s
    behaviour matters. Change one factor at a time so it is possible to tell what helped.
  </p>
  <p>
    A covered tray may reduce visible scatter for the household, but some cats may find it cramped
    or less comfortable. A very high-sided tray may contain litter yet create an access problem for
    a kitten, older cat or an animal recovering from illness.
  </p>

  <h2>Make Daily Cleaning Realistic</h2>
  <p>
    Plan where the scoop, replacement litter and waste bags will live without placing them on food
    preparation surfaces. Keep the route to a bin practical, protect the nearby floor with a
    washable mat where useful and leave enough clearance to clean around the whole tray.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remove urine and faeces daily and empty and clean the tray regularly, following the litter and
    tray instructions. Strong fragrances do not replace cleaning and may not suit the cat. Wash
    hands after handling the tray and seek health advice if someone in the household has particular
    infection-risk concerns.
  </p>

  <h2>Store Litter Without Creating Another Obstacle</h2>
  <p>
    Bulk litter can be heavy. Keep it dry, stable and close enough to refill the tray without
    awkward lifting, but do not narrow the cat’s route or the household walkway. Retain the product
    label and directions if litter is transferred into another container.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check whether the container can be cleaned and lifted when full. A very large tub may look tidy
    but become impractical in a small laundry or apartment.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan for Apartments, Rentals and Shared Rooms</h2>
  <p>
    In a smaller home, physically separate locations may require using two different rooms rather
    than finding a single dedicated cat area. Prioritise the cat’s access, then use a simple mat,
    screen or furniture arrangement only if it does not turn the tray into a cramped enclosure.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should protect floors with washable, non-slip solutions and avoid permanent cabinetry
    changes without approval. Ventilation matters, but an open window or balcony door should not be
    the only thing making the tray area usable.
  </p>

  <h2>Respond to Changes Instead of Blaming the Cat</h2>
  <p>
    If a cat begins toileting outside the tray, review access, cleanliness, tray number, litter and
    any recent household changes. Do not punish the cat. Persistent or sudden changes can have a
    medical cause, so seek veterinary advice rather than treating the problem only as cleaning or
    behaviour.
  </p>
  <p>Review the setup when:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>a kitten grows and the tray becomes cramped</li>
    <li>an older cat finds the entry or route difficult</li>
    <li>another cat or pet joins the home</li>
    <li>doors, appliances or furniture change the access path</li>
    <li>the household cannot keep the current position clean</li>
  </ul>

  <ProductDecisionBlock
    title="Litter-tray styles to compare after planning the locations"
    intro="These are product types, not ranked recommendations. Retain the cat's existing acceptable options while comparing a new tray, and change one factor at a time."
    items={trayTypes}
  />

  <h2>Let the Cat’s Access Lead the Decision</h2>
  <p>
    A good litter setup is not defined by how thoroughly the tray disappears from view. It gives the
    cat a quiet choice of accessible locations, enough room to use the tray and a cleaning routine
    the household can maintain.
  </p>
  <p>
    Plan those fundamentals before comparing covers, cabinets, automatic systems or decorative
    screens. If an enclosure makes access, inspection or cleaning harder, it has not improved the
    setup.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
